  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in most countries and is typically addressed under criminal legislation. Specific laws and penalties vary by jurisdiction, but generally, money laundering involves:\n\n1. Concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n2. Transforming \"dirty\" money into \"clean\" money\n3. Making funds from criminal activities appear legitimate\n\nMost countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws that criminalize these activities, with potential consequences including:\n\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Substantial fines\n- Imprisonment\n- Asset seizure\n- Professional sanctions\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prohibited under federal laws like the Bank Secrecy Act and the Money Laundering Control Act. Similarly, many other countries have comprehensive criminal statutes addressing this crime.\n\nFinancial institutions are typically required to implement compliance programs and report suspicious transactions to help prevent and detect money laundering activities.",
